article.description:
Every time the Indiana Fever needed a big
basket, Tamika Catchings came through. Every time they needed a
rebound or a big defensive play, it was Natalie Williams.
article.headline: Williams has 15 points and 17 boards
article.linkText: Williams, Catchings power Fever to victory over Sting
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Every time the Indiana Fever needed a big
basket, Tamika Catchings came through. Every time they needed a
rebound or a big defensive play, it was Natalie Williams.

"We worked hard in practice this week, especially on the last
four minutes of a game, switching and making stops," said
Williams, who scored 15 points and tied a franchise record with 17
rebounds as the Fever beat the Charlotte Sting 69-63 Saturday
night.

The victory, the Fever's first this season when scoring fewer
than 70 points, snapped a six-game losing streak and kept their
fading playoff hopes alive.

"That shows how much we have worked on defense," said
Williams, who also tied her career high with six assists, blocked
two shots, made one steal and joined Minnesota's Katie Smith as the
only women in U.S. professional basketball history with 4,000
career points.

"She was a monster on the boards," Indiana coach Nell Fortner
said. "She's a big-time player. She's earned all those 4,000
points."

Williams came to Indiana in a trade with San Antonio this
season. She also played three seasons with Portland in the
now-defunct ABL, where she was the league MVP in 1998. Her 15
points Saturday night raised her career total to 4,011.

Catchings led Indiana with 18 points, including two free throws
that put the Fever ahead for good at 62-60 with 1:19 remaining.
Williams then added two more free throws before Allison Feaster's
3-pointer brought Charlotte within 64-63.

Indiana closed the game with two free throws by Stephanie White,
one by Williams and two by Kristen Rasmussen to seal the victory.

Feaster led Charlotte with 21 points, but no other player for
the Sting had more than eight.

"It looks like they were more determined on the boards,"
Feaster said. "They were aggressive and drew more fouls."

The Fever hit 24 of 28 free throws, while Charlotte was 8-for-9.

"That was a huge discrepancy," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said.

Charlotte (16-14) remained in second place behind Detroit in the
Eastern Conference. The victory lifted Indiana (14-16) past New
York into fifth place in the East, one game behind Connecticut with
four games left in the regular season. The top four teams from each
conference advance to the playoffs.

"We need to keep our composure from here," Catchings said.
"When you win, it definitely helps your confidence, but we still
have areas to work on. ... As last year, with a do-or-die attitude,
if we're going to go down, we'll go down fighting."

The Fever hit their first five shots and jumped to an 11-2 lead
as they tried to end the second-longest losing streak in franchise
history.

But the Sting soon rallied with an 11-0 run for a 23-18 lead.

A 3-pointer by Coquese Washington pulled Indiana within two, but
Charlotte scored another seven in a row on a basket by Andrea
Stinson, a 3-pointer by Feaster and a fast-break layup by Dawn
Staley.

Charlotte led 34-28 at halftime and 58-52 before Indiana rallied
in the closing minutes.

A basket by Catchings made it 58-56 with 4:35 to go, then the
Fever scored their final 13 points on free throws.

The two teams play again on Wednesday in Charlotte. Indiana
leads the season series 2-1.
